"1669","Denham, Suffolk, England":"Denham, Suffolk, England, United Kingdom","Suffolk, England":"Suffolk, England","Denham, Suffolk, England ":"Denham, Suffolk, England, United Kingdom","Denham, Mid Suffolk District, Suffolk, England":"Denham, Suffolk, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Jordan","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English, German, French (mainly Alsace and Haute-Savoie), Polish, Czech, and Slovenian; Spanish and Hungarian (<b>Jordán</b>): from the Christian personal name or nickname <i>Jordan</i>. This is taken from the name of the river Jordan (Hebrew <i>Yarden</i>, a derivative of <i>yarad</i> ‘to go down’, i.e. to the Dead Sea). At the time of the Crusades it was a common practice for crusaders and pilgrims to bring back flasks of water from the river in which John the Baptist had baptized people, including Christ himself, and to use it in the christening of their own children. As a result <i>Jordan</i> became quite a common personal name."],"variants":[{"name":"Giordano","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Italian Angelo, Salvatore, Rocco, Antonio, Pasquale, Carmine, Vito, Domenic, Gaetano, Giuseppe, Sal, Santo.","Italian: from the personal name <i>Giordano</i>, an equivalent of   Jordan  ."]},{"name":"Jourdan","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Dominique, Gabrielle, Henri, Lucien, Pierre, Raoul, Yves.","English: variant of   Jordan  .","French (mainly southern): variant of   Jourdain  , a cognate of 2 below."]},{"name":"Jourdain","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French/Haitian Henri, Pierre, Fritz, Hans, Jacques, Rommel.","French, Breton (mainly Finistère), and West Indian (mainly Haiti, also Martinique and Dominican Republic): from the French personal name <i>Jourdain</i>, an equivalent of   Jordan  .","English (London, Derbyshire): French-influenced variant of   Jordan  ; compare 1 above."]},{"name":"Jordison","meanings":["English (North Yorkshire, Durham, and Northumberland): from a Middle English pet form, <i>Jordi</i>, of the male personal name   Jordan   + <i>-son</i>, or directly from a phonetic shortening of <i>Jordanson</i>."]},{"name":"Jorden","meanings":["English: variant of   Jordan  .","North German (mainly <b>Jörden</b>): probably a variant of   Jordan  . Compare   Yerden   and   Yerdon  ."]},{"name":"Judd","meanings":["English: from the Middle English personal name <i>Judde</i>, <i>Jutte</i>, a pet form of   Jordan  .","German: variant of   Jude  ."]},{"name":"Jorda","meanings":["Catalan (<b>Jordà</b>): from the personal name <i>Jordà</i> (see   Jordan  )."]},{"name":"Jerden","meanings":["English: from a variant of the personal name <i>Jurdon</i>, an old form of   Jordan  ."]},{"name":"Gordan","meanings":["German: variant of   Jordan  . The surname <i>Gordan</i> is very rare in Germany.","Irish (Wexford and Sligo): adopted as an Anglicized form of <b>Mag Mhuirneacháin</b> ‘son of <i>Muirneachán</i>’, a personal name from a diminutive of <i>muirneach</i> ‘lovable’."]},{"name":"Jordon","meanings":["English: variant of   Jordan  ."]}]},{"name":"Steven","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Variant of   Stephen  , reflecting the normal pronunciation of the name in the English-speaking world."],"variants":[{"name":"Stephen","meanings":["Usual English spelling of the name of the first Christian martyr (Acts 6–7), whose feast is accordingly celebrated next after Christ's own (  26 December ). His name is derived from the Greek word <i>stephanos</i> ‘garland, crown’."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Mrs Steven Jordan was born about 1589, in Suffolk, England, United Kingdom. She married Stephen Jordan about 1612, in Suffolk, England. They were the parents of at least 3 daughters."},"et":{"about 1589–":"umbes 1589–Surnud","1590–1669":"1590–1669","1615–Female":"1615–Surnud","1617–1677":"1617–1677","1622–1705":